window.ATLAS = {
  harnesses: [
    {key:'claude-code', name:'Claude Code'}, {key:'cursor', name:'Cursor'},
    {key:'replit', name:'Replit'}, {key:'openclaw', name:'OpenClaw'},
    {key:'codex', name:'Codex'}, {key:'shopify', name:'Shopify'},
    {key:'fin', name:'Intercom Fin'}, {key:'google', name:'Google'},
    {key:'langchain', name:'LangChain'}
  ],
  layers: [
    {num:1, name:'Brain', icon:'brain', q:'How does the agent know the world it operates in?', principle:'Trust the model to reason',
     tldr:'The model is brilliant and rootless: it knows everything in general and nothing about yours, and must be re-told every turn. Brain is everything that helps it get its bearings and pick an approach before it acts.',
     takeaway:'Where an outcome is verifiable, Brain mistakes are loud: a test catches the invented function, the broken split, the under-thought bug. Much of this scaffolding is a temporary crutch the next model deletes. Where an outcome is not verifiable, Brain mistakes are silent: nothing catches a confident wrong refund or a cross-repo bug behind a green build. The harder an outcome is to verify, the more the durable value sits in the harness.'},
    {num:2, name:'Hands', icon:'hand', q:'What can it touch, and what stops it?', principle:'Enforce at the tool boundary',
     tldr:'Hands governs the moment the agent stops thinking and starts touching things you care about. Thinking is reversible; touching often is not. So the harness stops asking nicely and starts enforcing at the boundary where the action fires.',
     takeaway:'The harness stops trusting the agent\u2019s in-the-moment judgment and enforces at the boundary instead, because by the time a destructive action is visibly wrong, it has already run. Four of these five capabilities answer silent failures that get worse as the agent grows more capable, so their scaffolding compounds. Only dispatch-and-retry is loud and staleable. The value is not in trusting the agent more; it is in building the gates it cannot reach.'},
    {num:3, name:'Coherence', icon:'link', q:'How does it not lose the thread?', principle:'Memory is the moat',
     tldr:'The model is stateless. It does not remember this morning, carry yesterday, or learn from a mistake between Tuesday and Wednesday. Every sense of continuity is the harness feeding the agent its own past, turn by turn.',
     takeaway:'Statelessness is permanent, not a ceiling the next model raises, and almost every memory failure is silent. Permanent plus silent is the recipe for durable value, which is why coherence is where the moat sits. And the provider whose model you rent has a structural incentive not to make your memory too efficient, because efficient memory bills fewer tokens. Whoever owns the curation, the compression, and the persistence owns the customer relationship.'},
    {num:4, name:'Feedback', icon:'trending-up', q:'How does it improve without a new model?', principle:'Harnesses compound, models reset',
     tldr:'The model does not learn from its mistakes. It arrives at every run exactly as it arrived at the first one. The feedback layer is the only thing that interrupts that loop: detect the failure, judge it, encode the permanent fix.',
     takeaway:'A model release resets the intelligence floor for everyone running it; a harness fix accumulates only for the team that built it. The two curves diverge, and the divergence is the moat\u2019s mechanism. Four signal channels (implicit, explicit, runtime, offline) exist to feed the fifth capability, Compounding Fixes. Signals that do not end in an encoded fix are decoration.'},
    {num:5, name:'Limitations', icon:'shield-x', q:'What won\u2019t it do, can\u2019t it do, won\u2019t it show?', principle:'Do not trust even the reasoning',
     tldr:'Every other layer trusts the model\u2019s reasoning at least a little. Limitations does not: the actions the harness forbids regardless of what the model concludes, the ceilings no configuration overcomes, and the things the harness will not let you see.',
     takeaway:'There are three kinds of walls, and confusing them is expensive. Walls that protect you: safety gates and structural ceilings. Walls that protect the builder: commercial controls that can misfire against you silently and follow the builder\u2019s competitive position rather than your use case. And walls that are simply real. Some walls protect you, some protect the builder, and from inside a session they look identical; the agent cannot tell you which is which.'}
  ],
  caps: []
};

